hese writers, Lawrence maintains, they share common insights. Their accounts overturn the dichotomy between adventure and domesticity, demonstrating something illusory within both the stability of home and the freedom of travel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishzForeign countriesxHistoriography. 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish prose literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish prose literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aTravel in literature. 0aTravel writingxHistory. 0aTravelers' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aVoyages and travelsxHistoriography. 0aWomen and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoriography. 0aWomen travelerszGreat BritainxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomenxTravelxHistoriography. 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aTravel Guides & Travel Writing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173249240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501732492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501732492/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles